<paragraph blockId="3.[136,516,842,868]" box="[136,516,842,868]" pageId="3" pageNumber="151">
<emphasis box="[136,516,842,868]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="151">Distribution, habitat, and ecology</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[136,1452,914,1301]" pageId="3" pageNumber="151">
<taxonomicName box="[136,334,914,940]" class="Bryopsida" family="Bryaceae" genus="Bryum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Bryales" pageId="3" pageNumber="151" phylum="Bryophyta" rank="species" species="glacierum">
<emphasis box="[136,334,914,940]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="151">Bryum glacierum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known from the Urumqi Glacier No. 1, Tianshan Mountain, which is the source region of the Urumqi River, within the Tianshan Mountain Range, 
<collectingCountry box="[745,816,950,976]" name="China" pageId="3" pageNumber="151">China</collectingCountry>
. As a reference glacier in the World Glacier Monitoring Service, Urumqi Glacier No. 1 is the best-observed glacier in 
<collectingCountry box="[828,899,986,1012]" name="China" pageId="3" pageNumber="151">China</collectingCountry>
. As currently known localities of the new species are characterized by an elevation above 
<quantity box="[582,668,1022,1049]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.6" pageId="3" pageNumber="151" unit="m" value="3600.0">3600 m</quantity>
, it is very frigid and dry in the winter. Warm weather can send melting water to the retreat range of the glacier in the summer. In this rather extreme unstable habitat, 
<taxonomicName box="[1189,1334,1058,1084]" class="Bryopsida" family="Bryaceae" genus="Bryum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Bryales" pageId="3" pageNumber="151" phylum="Bryophyta" rank="species" species="glacierum">
<emphasis box="[1189,1334,1058,1084]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="151">B. glacierum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a rather fragile and ephemeral plant. The deeply concave shape of the leaves may be related to covering and protecting the mature bulbils, allowing the leaves to remain imbricate as the bulbils grow to maturity (Koeckinger 
<emphasis box="[1309,1362,1130,1156]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="151">et al</emphasis>
. 2013). While inhabiting unpredictably varying environments, production of gemma by 
<taxonomicName box="[1044,1190,1166,1192]" class="Bryopsida" family="Bryaceae" genus="Bryum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Bryales" pageId="3" pageNumber="151" phylum="Bryophyta" rank="species" species="glacierum">
<emphasis box="[1044,1190,1166,1192]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="151">B. glacierum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be interpreted as a strategy to use available resources effectively and enhance its survival, and it can be an effective way to maintain and enlarge populations (
<bibRefCitation author="Newton, A. E. &amp; Mishler, B. D." box="[372,655,1238,1264]" pageId="3" pageNumber="151" pagination="127 - 145" refId="ref3465" refString="Newton, A. E., &amp; Mishler, B. D. (1994) The evolutionary significance of asexual reproduction in mosses. Journal of the Hattori Botanical Laboratory 76: 127 - 145." type="journal article" year="1994">Newton &amp; Mishler 1994</bibRefCitation>
). The most frequently associated bryophytes in this habitat are 
<taxonomicName authority="Schwagrichen (1811: 136)" authorityName="Schwagrichen" authorityPageNumber="136" authorityYear="1811" class="Bryopsida" family="Pottiaceae" genus="Tortula" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pottiales" pageId="3" pageNumber="151" phylum="Bryophyta" rank="species" species="mucronifolia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="151">Tortula mucronifolia</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Schwagrichen, C. F." box="[287,583,1274,1301]" pageId="3" pageNumber="151" refId="ref3527" refString="Schwagrichen, C. F. (1811) Species Muscorum Frondosorum, Supplementum Primum 1. Barth, Leipzig, 136 pp." type="book" year="1811">Schwägrichen (1811: 136)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Hedwig (1801: 118)" authorityName="Hedwig" authorityPageNumber="118" authorityYear="1801" box="[637,1106,1274,1300]" class="Bryopsida" family="Pottiaceae" genus="Barbula" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pottiales" pageId="3" pageNumber="151" phylum="Bryophyta" rank="species" species="unguiculata">
<emphasis box="[637,870,1274,1300]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="151">Barbula unguiculata</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Hedwig, J." box="[877,1106,1274,1300]" pageId="3" pageNumber="151" pagination="118 - 187" refId="ref3138" refString="Hedwig, J. (1801) Species Muscorum Frondosorum Descriptae. Leipzig, pp. 118 - 187." type="book chapter" year="1801">Hedwig (1801: 118)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
.
